table_with_only_examples:
{| class="wikitable " !Latin!!Translation!!Notes |- |''[[tabula rasa]]''||scraped tablet||Thus, "blank slate". Romans used to write on [[wax]]-covered wooden tablets, which were erased by scraping with the flat end of the [[stylus]]. [[John Locke]] used the term to describe the human [[mind]] at birth, before it had acquired any knowledge. |- |[[Tempora mutantur|''tempora mutantur et nos mutamur in illis'']]||the times are changing, and we change in them||16th century variant of two classical lines of Ovid: ''tempora labuntur'' ("time labors", ''Fasti'') and ''omnia mutantur'' ("everything changes", ''Metamorphoses''). See [[Tempora mutantur|entry]] for details. |- |''[[tempus fugit]]''||Time flees.
Time flies.||From [[Virgil]]'s ''[[Georgics]]'' (Book III, line 284), where it appears as ''fugit inreparabile tempus''. A common [[list of sundial mottos|sundial motto]]. See also ''tempus volat, hora fugit'' below. |- |''[[terminus post quem|terminus ante/post quem]]''||limit before/after which||In archaeology or history, refers to the date before which an artefact or feature must have been deposited. Used with ''terminus post quem'' (limit after which). Similarly, ''terminus ad quem'' (limit to which) may also refer to the latest possible date of a non-punctual event (period, era, etc.), while ''terminus a quo'' (limit from which) may refer to the earliest such date. |- |''[[terra incognita]]''||unknown land |}

|-
|''{{anchor|tabula gratulatoria}}tabula gratulatoria''||congratulatory tablet||A list of congratulations.
|-
|''{{anchor|talis qualis}}talis qualis''||just as such||"Such as it is" or "as such".
|-
|''{{anchor|taliter qualiter}}taliter qualiter''||somewhat
|-
|''{{Anchor|talium Dei regnum|talium regnum Dei|talium regnum caelorum}}talium Dei regnum''||for of such (little children) is the kingdom of God||from [[Mark the Evangelist|St Mark]]'s [[Gospel of Mark|gospel]] [[s:Bible (King James)/Mark#10:14|10:14]] "''[[s:la:Biblia Sacra Vulgata (Stuttgartensia)/Marcus|talium (parvuli) est enim regnum Dei]]''"; similar in [[Saint Matthew|St Matthew]]'s [[Gospel of Matthew|gospel]] [[s:Bible (King James)/Matthew#19:14|19:14]] "''[[s:la:Biblia Sacra Vulgata (Stuttgartensia)/Matthaeus|talium est enim regnum caelorum]]''" ("for of such is the kingdom of heaven"); motto of the [[Cathedral School, Townsville]].
|-
|''{{anchor|tanquam ex ungue leonem}}tanquam ex ungue leonem''||we know the lion by his claw||Said in 1697 by [[Johann Bernoulli]] about [[Isaac Newton]]'s anonymously submitted solution to Bernoulli's [[Later life of Isaac Newton#Bernoulli's mathematical challenge|challenge]] regarding the [[Brachistochrone curve]].
|-
|''{{anchor|tarde venientibus ossa}}tarde venientibus ossa''||To the late are left the bones |}

{| class="wikitable "
!Latin!!Translation!!Notes
|-
|''{{anchor|Te occidere possunt sed te edere non possunt nefas est}}Te occidere possunt sed te edere non possunt nefas est''||They can kill you, but they cannot eat you, it is against the law.||The motto of the fictional Enfield Tennis Academy in the [[David Foster Wallace]] novel ''[[Infinite Jest]]''. Translated in the novel as "They can kill you, but the legalities of eating you are quite a bit dicier".
|-
|''{{anchor|technica impendi nationi}}technica impendi nationi''||Technology impulses nations||Motto of [[Technical University of Madrid]]
|-
|''{{anchor|temet nosce}}temet nosce''||[[know thyself]]||A reference to the [[List of Greek phrases|Greek]] γνῶθι σεαυτόν (''gnothi seauton''), inscribed on the ''[[portico|pronaos]]'' of the [[Delphi#Temple of Apollo|Temple of Apollo]] at [[Delphi]], according to the Greek periegetic writer [[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]] (10.24.1). Rendered also with ''nosce te ipsum'', ''temet nosce'' ("thine own self know") appears in ''[[The Matrix]]'' translated as "know thyself".
|-
|''{{anchor|tempora heroica}}tempora heroica''||[[Greek Heroic Age|Heroic Age]]||Literally "Heroic Times"; refers to the period between the mythological [[Titanomachy]] and the (relatively) historical [[Trojan War]].
|-
|''{{anchor|tempus edax rerum}}tempus edax rerum''||time, devourer of all things||Also "time, that devours all things", literally: "time, gluttonous of things", ''edax'': adjectival form of the verb ''edo'' to eat. From [[Ovid]], Metamorphoses, 15, 234-236.
|-
|''{{anchor|tempus rerum imperator}}tempus rerum imperator''||time, commander of all things||"Tempus Rerum Imperator" has been adopted by the Google Web Accelerator project. It is shown in the "About Google Web Accelerator" page. Also, motto of [[Worshipful Company of Clockmakers]]. |}

{| class="wikitable "
!Latin!!Translation!!Notes
|-
|''{{anchor|tempus vernum}}tempus vernum''||spring time||Name of song by popular Irish singer [[Enya]]
|-
|''{{anchor|tempus volat, hora fugit}}tempus volat, hora fugit''||time flies, the hour flees
|-
|''{{anchor|tendit in ardua virtus}}tendit in ardua virtus''||virtue strives for what is difficult||Appears in [[Ovid]]'s ''[[Epistulae ex Ponto]]''
|-
|''{{anchor|teneo te Africa}}teneo te Africa''||I hold you, Africa!||[[The Twelve Caesars|Suetonius]] attributes this to [[Julius Caesar]], from when Caesar was on the African coast.
|-
|''{{anchor|tentanda via}}tentanda via''||The way must be tried||motto for [[York University]]
|-
|''{{anchor|ter in die}}ter in die <small>(t.i.d.)</small>''||thrice in a day||[[List of abbreviations used in medical prescriptions|Medical shorthand]] for "three times a day". |}

{| class="wikitable "
!Latin!!Translation!!Notes
|-
|''{{anchor|terminat hora diem; terminat auctor opus}}terminat hora diem; terminat auctor opus.''||The hour finishes the day; the author finishes his work.||Phrase concluding [[Christopher Marlowe]]'s play ''[[Doctor Faustus (play)|Doctor Faustus]]''.<ref>''[[s:The Tragedy of Doctor Faustus|The Tragedy of Doctor Faustus]]'' by [[Christopher Marlowe]] (at Wikisource)</ref>
|-
|''{{visible anchor|terra australis incognita}}''||unknown southern land||First name used to refer to the Australian continent
|-
|''{{anchor|terra nova}}terra nova''||new land||Latin name of [[Newfoundland (island)|Newfoundland]] (island portion of Canadian province of [[Newfoundland and Labrador]], capital- [[St. John's, Newfoundland and Labrador|St. John's]]), also root of French name of same, Terre-Neuve
|-
|''{{anchor|terras irradient}}terras irradient''||let them illuminate the lands||Or "let them give light to the world". An allusion to [[Isaiah]] 6.3: ''plena est omnis terra gloria eius'' ("the whole earth is full of his glory"). Sometimes mistranslated as "they will illuminate the lands" based on mistaking ''irradiare'' for a [[future tense|future]] [[Realis mood#Indicative|indicative]] third-[[grammatical conjugation|conjugation]] verb, whereas it is actually a [[present tense|present]] [[subjunctive mood|subjunctive]] first-conjugation verb. Motto of [[Amherst College]]; the college's original mission was to educate young men to serve God.
|-
|''{{visible anchor|Tibi cordi immaculato concredimus nos ac consecramus}}''||We consecrate and entrust ourselves to your Immaculate heart (O Mary).||The inscription found on top of the central door of the Minor Basilica of the Immaculate Conception, otherwise known as the [[Manila Cathedral]] in the Philippines
|-
|''{{anchor|timidi mater non flet}}timidi mater non flet''||A coward's mother does not weep|| A proverb from [[Cornelius Nepos]]'s ''Vita'' of Thrasybulus: ''praeceptum illud omnium in animis esse debet, nihil in bello oportere contemni, neque sine causa dici matrem timidi flere non solere'' (that old precept has to be held by all in our minds: nothing should be condemned in war, and it is for a reason that it is said the mother of a coward does not weep [for her cowardly son]). |}

{| class="wikitable "
!Latin!!Translation!!Notes
|-
|''{{anchor|toto cælo}}toto cælo''||by whole heaven||as far apart as possible; utterly.
|-
|''{{anchor|totus tuus}}totus tuus''||totally yours||Offering one's life in total commitment to another. The motto was adopted by [[Pope John Paul II]] to signify his love and servitude to [[Blessed Virgin Mary (Roman Catholic)|Mary the Mother of Jesus]].
|-
|''{{visible anchor|transire benefaciendo}}''||to travel along while doing good||Literally "beneficial passage." Mentioned in "The Seamy Side of History" (L'envers de l'histoire contemporaine, 1848), part of ''[[La Comédie humaine]]'', by [[Honoré de Balzac]], and ''[[Around the World in Eighty Days]]'' by [[Jules Verne]].
|-
|''{{anchor|tres faciunt collegium}}tres faciunt collegium''||three makes company||It takes three to have a valid group; three is the minimum number of members for an organization or a corporation.
|-
|''{{anchor|treuga Dei}}treuga Dei''||Truce of God||A decree by the medieval Church that all feuds should be cancelled during the [[Sabbath in Christianity|Sabbath]]—effectively from Wednesday or Thursday night until Monday. See also ''[[Peace and Truce of God]]''.
|-
|''{{visible anchor|tria juncta in uno}}''||Three joined in one||Motto of the [[Order of the Bath]] |}

{| class="wikitable "
!Latin!!Translation!!Notes
|-
|''{{visible anchor|Triste est omne animal post coitum, præter mulierem gallumque}}''||Every animal is sad after coitus except the human female and the rooster||
|-
|''{{visible anchor|tu autem Domine miserere nobis}}''||But Thou, O Lord, have mercy upon us||Phrase said at the end of biblical readings in the liturgy of the medieval church.  Also used in brief, "tu autem", as a ''memento mori'' [[epitaph]].
|-
|''{{visible anchor|tuitio fidei et obsequium pauperum}}''||Defence of the faith and assistance to the poor||Motto of the Association of Canadian Knights of the Sovereign and Military Order of Malta<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gg.ca/en/heraldry/public-register/project/1485|title=The Association of Canadian Knights of the Sovereign and Military Order of Malta|publisher=The Governor General of Canada|work=The Public Register of Arms, Flags, and Badges of Canada|access-date=19 February 2024}}</ref> and the [[Sovereign Military Order of Malta]].
|-
|''{{visible anchor|tu fui ego eris}}''||I was you; you will be me||Thus, "what you are, I was; what I am, you will be.". A ''memento mori'' [[gravestone]] inscription to remind the reader that death is unavoidable (cf. ''sum quod eris'').
|-
|''{{visible anchor|tu ne cede malis, sed contra audentior ito}}''||you should not give in to evils, but proceed ever more boldly against them||From [[Virgil]], ''[[Aeneid]]'', 6, 95. "Ne cede malis" is the motto of [[The Bronx]].
|-
|''{{visible anchor|tu stultus es}}''||you are stupid||''Motto'' for the [[News satire|satirical news]] organization, ''[[The Onion]]'' |}

{| class="wikitable "
!Latin!!Translation!!Notes
|-
|''{{anchor|tuebor}}tuebor''||I will protect||Found on the Great Seal on the flag of the state of [[Michigan]].
|-
|''{{anchor|tunica propior est pallio}}tunica propior est pallio''||A tunic is closer [to the body] than a cloak||From Plautus' ''Trinummus'' 1154. Equivalent to "blood is thicker than water" in modern English.
|-
|''{{visible anchor|turba}}''||colspan="2"|lit. 'uproar', 'disturbance', 'crowd'; in music, specifically in the [[Passion (music)|musical settings]] of the [[Passion of Jesus]], it refers to any text that is spoken by any group of people, including the [[disciple (Christianity)|disciples]], the Jews, or the soldiers.
|-
|''{{anchor|turris fortis mihi Deus}}turris fortis mihi Deus''||God is my strong tower||Motto of [[Clan Kelly]]
|-
|''{{anchor|tutum te robore reddam}}tutum te robore reddam''||I will give you safety by strength||Motto of [[Clan Crawford]]
|-
|''{{anchor|tuum est}}tuum est''||It's up to you||Motto of the [[University of British Columbia]] |}
